Then, I don't have the same error in the code from `node-pre-gyp/lib/pre-binding.js`:
```javascript
exports.find = function(package_json_path,opts) {
   if (!existsSync(package_json_path)) {
        throw new Error("package.json does not exist at " + package_json_path);
   }
   var package_json = require(package_json_path);
   versioning.validate_config(package_json);
   opts = opts || {};
   if (!opts.module_root) opts.module_root = path.dirname(package_json_path);
   var meta = versioning.evaluate(package_json,opts);
   return meta.module;
};
```

But now I have a new error, which is clearly weird.
It is on the require:
`var package_json = require(package_json_path);`

I get the error:
```
Uncaught (in promise) Error: Cannot find module "."
```

But if I set a breakpoint in the chrome devtools and execute it myself in the code, it works:
`Object {_from: "git+https://github.com/grpc/grpc.git#v1.6.x", _id: "grpc@1.6.6", _inBundle: false, _integrity: "sha1-kDDIjpxdCDKqV9W21yszpu+UVdo=", _location: "/grpc"…}`

So it looks now like a node/electron/grpc issue.
Do not know where to start from here, and how to fix this error.

Ok just found out why.
I launched my electron app like:
```javascript
    mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({
        show: false,
        width: 1024,
        height: 728,
    });

    mainWindow.loadURL(`file://${__dirname}/app.html`);

    // @TODO: Use 'ready-to-show' event
    //        https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/master/docs/api/browser-window.md#using-ready-to-show-event
    mainWindow.webContents.on('did-finish-load', () => {
        if (!mainWindow) {
            throw new Error('"mainWindow" is not defined');
        }
        mainWindow.show();
        mainWindow.focus();
    });
```

If an error occurred before the `did-finish-load` event has complete, the window was never showed.
Simply passing `show` parameter from `false` to `true` helped me see the app, and detect that I did not copy my `grpc_node.node` in another folder that was needed for the electron app to run.

I succeeded all this debug thanks to webstorm and its awesome debug tools with breakpoints! For people interested:
- https://blog.jetbrains.com/webstorm/2016/05/getting-started-with-electron-in-webstorm/
- https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/10445


In a nutshell, solving this issue was to put `grpc` as an external for webpack, compile my own `grpc_node.node` and placing it at the right paths.

I'll close that issue.
Thank you :)
